\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {By the time they reached the heart of Dover, the quiet of the cliffs had given way to the morning bustle. Cars honked as they squeezed past each other on narrow streets, students in varying shades of uniform filled the pavements, and the scent of bakery bread wafted from a shop nearby. The town, true to form, was alive with motion.}
\par\plain {Preston Secondary stood nestled between a row of old stone terraces and a small park, its wrought-iron gates painted deep blue, the school crest gleaming in gold above them. The building loomed tall\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 its Victorian bricks weathered by decades of sea air and teenage drama. Even now, Eddie could spot a cluster of students huddled near the entrance, laughing loudly, dodging around teachers with clipboards.}
\par\plain {He slowed the bike to a stop just outside the gate.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Well,\u8221\'94 he said, turning slightly in the saddle. \u8220\'93Here we are. First day of the rest of your life.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Torrie swung off the bike, adjusting her satchel and brushing imaginary dust off her sweater. She looked smaller all of a sudden\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 still stubborn, still trying not to show nerves, but Eddie recognized that look in her eyes. He\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d worn it once too.}
\par\plain {He glanced up at the school, expression softening. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You know,\u8221\'94 he said, \u8220\'93I used to hate this place.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Torrie blinked. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Really?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Mm-hmm.\u8221\'94 He looked at the gates as if they might remember him. \u8220\'93It was rough sometimes. I didn\u8217\'92t really fit in. But,\u8221\'94 he paused, \u8220\'93I still learned a lot here.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Torrie didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t say anything, just looked at him.}
\par\plain {He smiled, a little wistful. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It wasn\u8217\'92t all bad of course, there are some fond memories.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {She looked down at her shoes. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I\u8217\'92m not gonna have a rough time like you, right?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Eddie\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s smile widened as he knelt a little to meet her eye level. \u8220\'93You\u8217\'92re gonna do great. You\u8217\'92re way braver than I ever was. And smarter.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Flattery,\u8221\'94 she mumbled, grinning.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I\u8217\'92m being honest here.\u8221\'94 He tapped her satchel. \u8220\'93You\u8217\'92ve got this. And if it ever gets too weird, too loud, or too hard\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 you tell someone. Don\u8217\'92t go it alone.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Torrie nodded, then, unexpectedly, flung her arms around him. Eddie blinked, caught off guard, but returned the hug with a tight squeeze.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Bestest of luck, little genius,\u8221\'94 he murmured.}
\par\plain {Then, with one last glance, Torrie turned and walked through the school gates, disappearing into the tide of students.}
\par\plain {Eddie stayed a moment longer, watching, the sun climbing higher over the rooftops. Preston hadn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t changed much\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 but he had. He turned his bike slowly, the wind brushing against his face, and pedaled back into the streets of Dover, not quite smiling, but not sad either.}
